ll be a Feature day. Ori the Opening Night\ntm\n\"The Old Guaid'' and most conser\nvative wing of the Republican party\nis gradually cementing its power to\nv. ti i ris the nomination of Gov. Low\n00 n.\nIr the contest for delegates whole\nsa!e charges for bribery, corruption\n'end color diseriniination, have filled\ntif air.\nIn an intervicw with newspaner\nmen, Gov. Lowden announced that\nhe was \"not in favor of any evading\"\nof the prohibition amendment.\nBT. J. PUBLIC\nSCHOOLS HOLD j\nFESTIVAL\nTwo\nat\nFine Entertainnients\nthe St. Johnsbury i\nAi mory on Friday\nI rreaericK une, ashington cor\nresponder.t of the Public Ledger, who\ntestified at the Senate investigatoin\nI of campaign expenses of a so-calleri\ni California \"slush\" fund of $100 003\nmet Senator Johnson here. In about'\nfi-eely on what eemeri a steadily ad- i5e\"1 Jonm?\" nt\",e- ln DOUl\nvincing nviket. Now thev don't \u00f9el a sond aft\"' ;n,lntrf0.d,\u00eccVv,? Sna;\nm ry happy to have their loans cali- hr Johnson lasheri out at ile and tr l,\nUnder the direction of Albert W.\nSmith, leader of music in our public\nschools, ihe children gave their first\nl'i'blic festival at the Arr.iory Friday\nbeforc la 'Ve and appreciative audi\nences. The children in the grades\nwere the entertainers at the matinee\n;vj the evening festival was given by\ni Junior High School and orches-\nMis.; Sylvia Ricker was the ac-\ny iihijj m iictyt- uicii ivnns i u i u4 .1\ned, and to be forced to sell on a drop- I \",c uc\" C\" f.mpani. at botti periormapccs.\nPlug market. The experience is Ied- i \u00cc\u00ccwwa5 \"damnable lie. The great The afternoon festival incl\ning many business men to prcuict\nthfit oi-ders will omc in rather slow\nfor the next few months.\nThen .if course there is the revival\nof Eiropc. This is proceeding much\nf;kster than the business community\nrealizes. .The cable brings the big\nDo Not Forget\nWe sell\nSATURDAY'S ONLY\nXard 25c per Ib\nSalt Pork 5 lbs for $1.00\n3 fbs Bacon $1.00\nCooked meats of ali\nkinds. 'v\nWe elose Wednesday\nat 12.30\nWeeks Barrett\n1 heodorc Kooseveit never gave\nman a worse riressing down.\nIn Chicago the Hoover boom has\ndwindled to almost nil. Mention of\nhis canriidacy in the hotel lobbies is\nmet with a smile even though the\namused person generally admits that\nthe demanri for Hoover is almost un\nprecedented in American histoiy. But\nHoover has not a single delegate, and\nfew have considered nini as a second\nchoice. It is a politicai convention\nand politicians now hold the\nfloor in Chicago and not \"the plain\npeople.\"\nIn connection with the\nART BAZAAR\nMiss Evelyn Blackburn wBl conduct\na Woman's Exchange\nTHE F1SHERMAN\nThe f\u00ec-;hciman is not ;:o common a\ntype as he used to ho. As ciHes and\ntowns grow more populous, the num\nber of fishablc streams and lakes\nwithin reyh riows less. Those tint\nare frequented by the finny trible be\ncome wideiy known. Automobile par\nties travel manv hours to reach them.\nYet there never was a time when\nthe rxperi'-nces which the fisherni:n\nloves were more welcome. People\nare sick cf the everlasting turmoil\nand recrin inatior of the times. They\ncan't escape these dilhculties of living\nthat so crowds upon them. Eut they\ndo long to get away sometimes a.id\nforget it for a while.\nNever hefore diri the quiet neace of\na shudy hicok, or the cairn ripples of\na sparking lake, scem naif so \u00ecnvit\ning. When ycu get out into some se\ncludod snot, with the game played !-e-\nKnights of Pythias\nRegular meeting of Apollo Lodge,\nNo. 2, Tucsday evening, June 8, at\n8 o'clock.\nH. C. Ingersoll, C. C.\nII. C Abbott. K. R. S.\n1 \u00c9N7\nPASSUMPSIC LODGE, F. A. M.\nArthur L. Graves, W. M.\nFred H. Dolloff, Sec.\nHaswell Royal Arch Chapter\nStateri Convocation Fridav, June\n11, at 7.S0 o'clock.'\nr r. F. C. Beck. E. II. P.\nR. A. Vearl, Secy.\nPalestine Commandery, No. S, K. T.\nSpecial Conclave, Thursdav even\ning, June lOth at 7..n,0. Work, R. C.\nM. A good attend